INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '3c7354df-4e0b-481a-8148-c19c9e9879ec',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Ansible Multi-Environment Inventories — One Codebase, Three Environments$escape$,
  $escape$Ansible handles dev/staging/prod separation through directory-scoped inventories paired with group_vars. Instead of a flat hosts file, structure each environment as its own inventory directory containing hosts.yml and a group_vars/ subtree. Your playbooks stay untouched — only the -i flag changes at runtime.

Define shared defaults in group_vars/all/vars.yml, then override per-environment in group_vars/webservers/vars.yml within each inventory directory. Variable precedence resolves environment-specific values at play time without any conditionals in your roles.

For secrets, pair each environment's group_vars with an ansible-vault encrypted vault.yml file. Use a per-environment vault password file (.vault_pass_prod, .vault_pass_staging) referenced via --vault-password-file, never hardcoded. Add all vault password files to .gitignore.

To enforce environment promotion hygiene, add a pre_tasks block that asserts ansible_limit is set, preventing accidental all-host runs against prod. Combine this with tagged plays (--tags deploy) to gate destructive operations behind explicit intent rather than relying on operator discipline.$escape$,
  $escape$inventories/
  dev/
    hosts.yml
    group_vars/
      all/vars.yml        # db_port: 5432, env: dev
      webservers/vars.yml # replicas: 1
  prod/
    hosts.yml
    group_vars/
      all/vars.yml        # db_port: 5432, env: prod
      all/vault.yml       # db_password: !vault |
      webservers/vars.yml # replicas: 4

# Run against prod only:
# ansible-playbook -i inventories/prod site.yml --vault-password-file .vault_pass_prod$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
