INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2ae3da3f-aef5-43b1-936b-670af7d7cff1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Ansible Secrets — Vault Integration and Why Plaintext Vars Will Burn You$escape$,
  $escape$Storing secrets in `group_vars/` or `host_vars/` as plaintext is the fastest way to leak credentials through version control. Ansible gives you two clean paths out.

First: `ansible-vault encrypt_string` wraps individual values inline — no separate vault file needed. Mark encrypted strings with `!vault` and Ansible decrypts them at runtime using `--vault-password-file` or `ANSIBLE_VAULT_PASSWORD_FILE`.

Second, and preferred for production: pull secrets from HashiCorp Vault or AWS Secrets Manager using `community.hashi_vault.hashi_vault` or `amazon.aws.aws_ssm` lookup plugins. Secrets are fetched at play runtime, never written to disk, and never appear in `ansible --diff` output or log files.

Critical: set `no_log: true` on any task that registers or uses a secret variable. Without it, Ansible prints variable values on failure. Also disable `ANSIBLE_DEBUG` in CI — it dumps all variable values. Use `ansible-lint` with the `no-log-password` rule to enforce this in pipelines. Your state — inventory, vars, facts cache — should contain zero secret material.$escape$,
  $escape$- name: Fetch DB password from HashiCorp Vault
  hosts: app_servers
  vars:
    db_password: "{{ lookup('community.hashi_vault.hashi_vault',
      'secret=secret/data/prod/db:password
      url=https://vault.internal:8200
      auth_method=aws_iam
      role_id=prod-app') }}"
  tasks:
    - name: Configure database connection
      ansible.builtin.template:
        src: db.conf.j2
        dest: /etc/app/db.conf
        mode: '0600'
      no_log: true$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
