INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '1e16a171-0c5f-428e-b63b-d3aa90cef1be',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Ansible Linting — ansible-lint and yamllint for Consistent Playbook Style$escape$,
  $escape$Ansible has no built-in formatter, but combining ansible-lint with yamllint gives you enforced consistency across playbooks, roles, and collections. ansible-lint checks for anti-patterns: using command/shell instead of purpose-built modules, missing name attributes on tasks, incorrect handler notifications, and FQCN violations (e.g. copy instead of ansible.builtin.copy). yamllint handles the YAML layer — trailing spaces, indentation width, line length, and quote style.

Define both configs at repo root. In .ansible-lint, set warn_list vs error on rule severity, skip_list for intentional bypasses, and profile: production to catch the strictest violations. In .yamllint, pin indent.spaces: 2, line-length.max: 160, and truthy.allowed-values: [true, false] to prevent yes/no/on/off surprises.

Run both in pre-commit hooks and CI. ansible-lint --fix auto-remediates many violations (FQCN rewrites, missing names). Pair with molecule lint to catch role-level issues before they hit staging. Enforcing yamllint+ansible-lint as blocking CI gates eliminates entire classes of subtle bugs caused by inconsistent variable quoting and module misuse.$escape$,
  $escape$# .ansible-lint
profile: production
warn_list:
  - yaml[line-length]
skip_list:
  - role-name  # monorepo layout exception

# .yamllint
---
extends: default
rules:
  indentation:
    spaces: 2
  line-length:
    max: 160
  truthy:
    allowed-values: ["true", "false"]

# pre-commit config
- repo: https://github.com/ansible/ansible-lint
  rev: v24.2.0
  hooks:
    - id: ansible-lint$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
